<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="94214126-66cc-5486-9b1c-6bd2b2f1e27c" activityNameId="29420ac5-41bf-52e2-a753-a0d992195072" parentActivityId="fe498c5a-2ec5-5f26-bab7-ba45eabc96fa" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">natural gas, high pressure, import from US</activityName>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts from the outbound gate of the natural gas production plants.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This dataset describes the transport needed for an average export of natural gas from the place of origin. Gas losses and emissions during seasonal storage are included. The dataset “Natural gas, burned in gas turbine” is used to account for the emissions and infrastructure of the operational energy requirements of the storage capacities. The infrastructure of the storage is neglected in this study as it is assumed to be insignificant. The activity ends at the "entry gate" of national markets for natural gas at high pressure.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the import of natural gas [m3] from United States to Turkey. The gas inputs to this import activity shares of gas supplied through LNG import and via long-distance pipeline for the specific combination of origin and destination. The average transport distance from the countries of origin to European region was adapted from previous studies, whereas additional combinations of supply-demand geographies were estimated for other regions.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Reference(s):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Bussa, M., N. Jungbluth, Ch. Meili (2023) Life cycle inventories for long-distance transport and distribution of natural gas. ESU-services Ltd. Schaffhausen, Switzerland. Available from: http://esu-services.ch/data/public-lci-reports/</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="5020424a-5b73-4722-8000-ac205dbd592d">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">3520:Manufacture of gas; distribution of gaseous fuels through mains</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="1347b0a0-7d7e-11de-9ae2-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">TR</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Turkey</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">An average leakage rate of 0.1% of the gas stored was used by Bussa et al. (2023), based on previous studies. Furthermore, Bussa et al. assumed that 15% of total natural gas supply is temporarily stored, based on European Commission (2015), for all geographies covered.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2021-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Transport modes investigated for 2021.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
